{{Expand German|Archäophyt|date=May 2016}}

An '''archaeophyte''' is a [[plant]] species which is non-native to a geographical region, but which was an [[introduced species]] in "ancient" times, rather than being a modern introduction. Those arriving after are called [[Neophyte (botany)|neophyte]]s. In Britain, archaeophytes are considered to be those species first introduced prior to 1492, when [[Christopher Columbus]] arrived in the [[New World]] and the [[Columbian Exchange]] began.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Preston |first=Christopher D. |last2=Pearman |first2=David A. |last3=Hall |first3=Allan R. |date=1 July 2004 |title=Archaeophytes in Britain |url=https://academic.oup.com/botlinnean/article/145/3/257/2420246 |journal=[[Botanical Journal of the Linnean Society]] |language=en |volume=145 |issue=3 |pages=257–294 |doi=10.1111/j.1095-8339.2004.00284.x |issn=0024-4074 |access-date=2018-07-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180306102951/https://academic.oup.com/botlinnean/article/145/3/257/2420246 |archive-date=2018-03-06 |dead-url=no }}</ref>

