'''Pheophorbide a''' is the product of [[chlorophyll]] breakdown. It is used as a [[photosensitizer]].<ref>{{cite journal | author=Chen, K.| title=Novel photosensitizer-protein nanoparticles for Photodynamic therapy: Photophysical characterization and in vitro investigations| journal=Journal of Photochemistry and Photobiology B: Biology| year=2009 | volume=96 | issue=1 | pages=66–74 | doi=10.1016/j.jphotobiol.2009.04.006|display-authors=etal}}</ref>
Photodynamic therapy (PDT) with several photosensitizers is a promising modality for the treatment of cancer. In this study, the therapeutic effect of PDT using the synthetic photosensitizer pheophorbide a (Pa-PDT) was examined in AT-84 murine oral squamous cell carcinoma (OSCC) cells.
